1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:23,000
So what I'm going to do is just sort of record a little opening announcement for the camera.

3
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:27,000
So when they transcribed, then nobody's here.

4
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:31,000
And then like sort of like we did at the SNCC reunion,

5
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:36,000
we'll just sort of walk through chronologically, I think that sounds good to you.

6
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:38,000
Whatever it's good for you.

7
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:40,000
So good afternoon.

8
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:43,000
Today is Thursday, April 11, 2013.

9
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:46,000
We are in Culver City, California.

10
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:52,000
Recording for the Southern oral history program at UNC Chapel Hill,

11
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:58,000
and the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

12
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:03,000
I'm the interviewer today, David Cline, with videographer John Bishop,

13
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:07,000
and today we are talking to Mr. Rick Tuttle,

14
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:11,000
and I want to thank you very much for joining us and being part of this project.

15
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:12,000
Glad to be here.

16
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:18,000
So what I'm going to do to start with, I feel very strongly that it's starting with someone's childhood.

17
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:23,000
And I really believe that the things that we go on to do later are very much important,

18
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:25,000
by where we came from often.

19
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:34,000
So with an eye toward that, as you can tell us a little bit about your upbringing and how you might see that figuring in your later work.

20
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:37,000
Well, I was born in New Haven, Connecticut,

21
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:44,000
and my father came from a paternal, a long time, New England family,

22
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:47,000
a subtle New Haven in 1638.

23
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:54,000
My grandmother Tuttle's grandfather,

24
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:58,000
rode with the Connecticut regimen,

25
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:06,000
that a minute or two after the Massachusetts 54th was mowed down of the assault on Charleston at Fort Wagner.

26
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:11,000
A minute or two later, these boys from Connecticut,

27
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:15,000
who had been posted on the sea islands off Charleston,

28
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:18,000
they were on the next assault wave,

29
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:24,000
and he took a, this is a well-known story inside the family.

30
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:26,000
That's the relevance to this.

31
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:31,000
And Grandma Tuttle's grandfather, a blessed memory, took a bullet,

32
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:34,000
and later died on the Petersburg front.

33
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:37,000
There's a recent Lincoln movie out called Lincoln,

34
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:43,000
came out this year, where he had a grown-up person's decision to make,

35
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:48,000
whether to accept the federal Confederate commissioners and make the peace.

36
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:53,000
They'd come back into the union and block the 13th Amendment to abolish slavery,

37
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:55,000
which is why they wanted to get in when they did.

38
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:58,000
Vice President Stevens was there, and the half of Jefferson,

39
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:00,000
he was a serious envoy.

40
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:03,000
And Lincoln made a grown-up decision.

41
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:04,000
I would have made the same decision.

42
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:10,000
That is, take thousands and thousands more casualties of the siege of Richmond and Petersburg.

43
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:17,000
Don't make the peace win the war at abolish slavery.

44
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:25,000
The iconic photo of that that's on all the postings around urban areas,

45
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:29,000
so the advertised movie shows Lincoln with his entourage on horseback,

46
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:34,000
riding through the casualties and the dead bodies at Petersburg,

47
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:39,000
in the figurative sense that is my grandmother's grandfather.

48
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:43,000
He died on the Petersburg front, was wounded at Fort Wagner,

49
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:45,000
and died on the Petersburg front.

50
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:49,000
Now we would hear about Monroe Gillette from time to time.

51
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:52,000
My other side of the family was Arkansas.

52
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:57,000
And my mother's family had stories to tell of their own,

53
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:00,000
of reconstruction and the Civil War, which were very different stories.

54
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:06,000
Stories of torture, stories of what happened when the union army came through,

55
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:08,000
and they were very bitter stories.

56
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:11,000
These are very vivid to a little boy.

57
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
I'm the eldest and the family on that side,

58
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:17,000
who listened to these stories from Mimmie, on the one hand,

59
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:21,000
my mother's mother, and Grandma Tuttle, my father's mother.

60
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:24,000
So I was raised in the stories,

61
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:26,000
and they couldn't even agree on what they were to call it,

62
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:29,000
the Civil War, the war between the states.

63
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:31,000
And very vivid memories.

64
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:34,000
On several occasions, when they happened to be visiting at the same time,

65
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:38,000
we were living in Arkansas, and Connecticut, Rhode Island,

66
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:40,000
and Northern New York.

67
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:42,000
And we were old school family.

68
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:45,000
One of the other was usually whether it's five or six months a year,

69
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,000
a respected grandmother.

70
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:49,000
But they would sometimes get there at the same time.

71
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:52,000
And the clatter of dishes is one or another in silver.

72
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:55,000
It's one of the other got up and stormed away from the table.

73
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:58,000
Vivified this history.

74
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:01,000
And that made some impact.

75
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:08,000
Later, dad, there's a story in the family where dad,

76
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:15,000
well, by the way, when Roger Lat got into the Civil War as a man in his early 30s.

77
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:19,000
And like much of the Union Army in 64 when the enlistments ran out,

78
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:21,000
he wasn't a draftee.

79
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:25,000
He'd been a 49er as a young man, and then he went up there.

80
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:28,000
One of the fascinating things about the Union Army,

81
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:31,000
in his case, he was an enlistee, not a draftee,

82
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:34,000
is they could have walked away from the war after three years.

83
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:35,000
They re-upped.

84
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:38,000
A vast number of those soldiers re-upped,

85
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:40,000
and continued the fight.

86
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:42,000
He was one of them who did so.

87
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:46,000
Dad went into that tradition.

88
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:50,000
My father in the Hitler War, the war against fascism,

89
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:55,000
the Hitler Alliance, went into the Marine Corps at age 36.

90
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:01,000
And they made fun of them until they won the Almarine Hundred-yard Ash at Parris Island.

91
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:09,000
After the war, I remember we were bomb and my mother and I,

92
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:14,000
my brother and other brother, who was pregnant with Alan.

93
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:19,000
We were down in Arkansas in 44-45 in Jonesboro,

94
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:22,000
not far from Memphis, across the river from Memphis.

95
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:24,000
And we were coming back, we took the Memphis train,

96
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:28,000
and we were coming back up to Cincinnati,

97
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:32,000
where we would switch trains, and go on into New York,

98
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:34,000
and up to New Haven, and go back home.

99
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:37,000
Family made their decision to go back to the North.

100
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:42,000
And a powerful story in my memory is that,

101
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:48,000
I'm pertinent to all this, is the train broke down north of Memphis.

102
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:50,000
A lot of the rolling stock was very old.

103
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:53,000
They hadn't been trains built since the 1920s.

104
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:55,000
The pressure and years followed by with the Second War.

105
00:06:55,000 --> 00:07:00,000
And the joke was that all the people who lived on the fighting men and women who lived in Oregon,

106
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:02,000
California, New York, fought in Europe,

107
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:05,000
all the people who lived in the Carolinas of Virginia and Maine

108
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:08,000
and Connecticut, New York, fought the war in the Pacific.

109
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:10,000
So the whole nation seemed to be on the move.

110
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:13,000
The trains were jammed, the hotels were jammed,

111
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:17,000
and the train broke down just outside of the North of Memphis.

112
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:19,000
And we were all anxiously looking at it,

113
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:22,000
or my dad was a little boy, but I knew what was going on.

114
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:24,000
I was five going on, six going on, looking at their watches,

115
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:27,000
and fretting about, would we be able to make the New York train?

116
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:31,000
There was nowhere to stay in Cincinnati.

117
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:36,000
And we were this little family, and mom was pregnant with a fourth child, my sister.

118
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:41,000
And me, the man of the family at age five, almost six,

119
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:46,000
dad was with us, and mom and my two brothers.

120
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:51,000
And we pulled in, as we pulled into the train station at the Cincinnati train station,

121
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:53,000
a great old fashioned train station.

122
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:55,000
There were rows and rows of tracks.

123
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:58,000
At the far end, there were no other trains between us.

124
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:03,000
We could see the New York train, and it was, as the trains do,

125
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:08,000
I mean, ready to roll, it was, pfff, pfff, and dad came off the train,

126
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:11,000
and turned to the, as he was getting off, turns to the conductor,

127
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:15,000
it was to me it had pleasant professional conversations,

128
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:18,000
and checking out the time, and said, can you help us?

129
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:22,000
And a little family, we have to walk all the way over there,

130
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:24,000
we'll never make it, that train's out of here.

131
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:27,000
It already was about two minutes to pull out.

132
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:32,000
And the conductor said, sir, I'm sorry, I can't help,

133
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:35,000
I mean, schedule, and the companies, and all that stuff.

134
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:41,000
Dad then turned to the porter, African-American,

135
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:45,000
the sleeping car, Porters Union, a fellow brand-of's Union, as it turned.

136
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:50,000
And he turned to the porter, and said, can you help me?

137
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:51,000
Can you help us?

138
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:55,000
The porter, we weren't in the sleeping car,

139
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:59,000
the porter's were around, they saw the situation grasp it instantly.

140
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:02,000
And dad, Porter looked at my father, my father,

141
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:05,000
that was in uniform, as I remember, my father looked at him,

142
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:09,000
they looked at each other, and dad stepped closer,

143
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:16,000
and showed him something, and it was a card,

144
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:21,000
and the porter turned, looked up the line to another porter,

145
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:25,000
and he was a younger man, I remember that way, like that.

146
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:29,000
He went like that, that train stopped,

147
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:34,000
and we, in a orderly way, walked over,

148
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:38,000
and we're welcomed onto the other train, I said to my father,

149
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:41,000
what is it, dad, that you showed him, there's no money,

150
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:45,000
there's no greenback, I didn't know much about the world,

151
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:49,000
but I saw what I saw, and my father pulled out the card

152
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:53,000
and showed it to me, the card was a card of the NAACP.

153
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:56,000
My father had been an active member of the NAACP,

154
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:59,000
the National Association of the Vance of the Colored People,

155
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:02,000
in New Haven, Connecticut, had coached my father,

156
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:05,000
a great athlete, and also Marine Corps,

157
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:09,000
100-yard dash, all that, and it was also probably the finest

158
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:13,000
high school track coach in New England at the time,

159
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:16,000
they won nine out of ten Connecticut State Championships,

160
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:19,000
and ran the Great New Haven Harrier Teams,

161
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:23,000
hundreds of young men, a fair number of whom were African-American.

162
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:28,000
And so, I was a little boy around that scene,

163
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:30,000
though he was no longer a coach, he had become a principal,

164
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:33,000
but around that scene, and the school where he was principal

165
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:37,000
is predominantly African-American, the Dixwell Avenue area of New Haven.

166
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:42,000
And my father was engaged civically in various ways,

167
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:45,000
not in a particularly political man in the electoral sense,

168
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:47,000
but civically engaged.

169
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:50,000
And that story, as always stuck in my mind,

170
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:53,000
is what organization can do.

171
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:57,000
To be organized, and in this case, to be organized around the right cause,

172
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:00,000
is something made a powerful impact on me,

173
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:02,000
and more I learned later about the sleeping car portals,

174
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:06,000
I realized just exactly what a good move that was.

175
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:10,000
And any of them, I grew up in the North,

176
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:13,000
and later went to Wesleyan in Connecticut,

177
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:18,000
high school, and I went to 10 different schools before high school.

178
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:20,000
Moved around a lot. The war was on a lot of people

179
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:22,000
removing around them in the states.

180
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:25,000
And then wound up in the Platt-Sprick High School,

181
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:30,000
a terrific place, like a lot of us work my way through,

182
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:34,000
all those construction jobs, and so on.

183
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:38,000
And even with a bit of a farmer for a while,

184
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:42,000
it was a little guy delivered newspapers for three years.

185
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:47,000
And went to Wesleyan University in Middletown, Connecticut.

186
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:54,000
When I was there, when I arrived, we walked in and joined a fraternity.

187
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:59,000
The Alpha Chi-Row fraternity, and our group of chaps at the local,

188
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:04,000
we were local, one of the locals, I think 27 locals,

189
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:11,000
had a year or two earlier, discovered a clause

190
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:15,000
that was a Christian-only clause, or put it this way,

191
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:18,000
to be a member of the fraternity,

192
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:21,000
had pledged allegiance to Jesus Christ.

193
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:25,000
And also, there was a hidden clause, as I understand it,

194
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:28,000
that was, I never saw that clause,

195
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:32,000
but our people, or my paternity brother said it was a hidden clause,

196
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:35,000
about whites only.

197
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:38,000
In any event, we became involved over the fourth,

198
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:40,000
I wound up being president of the fraternity,

199
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:42,000
I had an active in the house, a group of,

200
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:45,000
really quite a remarkable group of people,

201
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:50,000
it turned out, both in college terms, alumni terms,

202
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:52,000
and also just generally, civically.

203
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:55,000
And we got involved in the battle against discrimination

204
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:57,000
in that fraternity.

205
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:00,000
I don't think it took a lot of guts for us to be involved,

206
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:03,000
even in the post-Joh McCarthy era, to be involved

207
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:06,000
in the civil rights fight in the middle of a liberal arts college

208
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:08,000
in the Connecticut River Valley.

209
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:11,000
But it got us familiar with the vocabulary and the concepts

210
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:13,000
of civil rights.

211
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:17,000
And we were, correctly, we were one of three fraternities,

212
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:22,000
widely seen out of 12, who engaged in this struggle.

213
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:24,000
Some of them didn't have to, they didn't have these clauses,

214
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:26,000
others chose not to.

215
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:31,000
And I served on the civil rights committee of the campus.

216
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:35,000
But the main arena was working on these issues,

217
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:38,000
we're trying to retain the property and the break from our national.

218
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:40,000
And we did, we gave them one year to change

219
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:43,000
when they didn't do it, we fired them.

220
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:44,000
And...

221
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:46,000
That was what you're...

222
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:50,000
Well, I arrived in 1957.

223
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:54,000
I broke a hand and playing basketball, as a matter of fact.

224
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:59,000
And the joke was, oh my god, coach, it's Tuttle shooting hand.

225
00:13:59,000 --> 00:14:01,000
They put me in the games anyway, I had a ball.

226
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:04,000
It's Tuttle shooting hand, the coach said, so what?

227
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:10,000
And I had to have that, but I broke my hand a couple of times.

228
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:13,000
It's the second time I took advantage of that to think of you're off,

229
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:15,000
which I did.

230
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:19,000
And did a lot of reading, a lot of thinking that you're happened to be 1960,

231
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:22,000
which is a heck of a year to take off.

232
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:26,000
I think it made some difference in my life, because I graduated in 1962.

233
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:32,000
The battle with the fraternity national went on through those years.

234
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:39,000
Were you there at Wesleyan when the city movement began in the town of South?

235
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:46,000
Yeah, my fall of 1957, the little rock took place.

236
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:52,000
And there's another feature to my upbringing there.

237
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:55,000
I was there as a little guy.

238
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:59,000
I saw something of segregation, saw a bit of it.

239
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:02,000
That was a little guy though, I was five and six.

240
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:09,000
Went back down to visit family members in my, just before going off to college,

241
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:13,000
a year or so before, sort of, sophomore junior year, and saw something of segregation

242
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:19,000
did not like what I saw, heard a lot about it, et cetera.

243
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:25,000
But I had come to a subtle opinion that this segregation business was a bad idea,

244
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:30,000
a bad idea for the people who were being affected by it,

245
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:39,000
who were Negro, African-American, and also in some ways crippling for whites.

246
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:45,000
And then, in addition to that, I thought a bad idea in many respects,

247
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:49,000
including voting rights, public accommodations, other things.

248
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:54,000
But our battle was over here in this fraternity, and then what very pertinent

249
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:57,000
sit-ins took place.

250
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:09,000
And I was out of college up in Plattsburgh when the Woolworth's sit-ins were taking place.

251
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:17,000
And I have trouble now recalling whether I actually went down and actually was in the line,

252
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:21,000
sort of picket line around the Woolworths in Plattsburgh.

253
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:23,000
I know I wasn't that middle-town.

254
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:25,000
I don't think I actually was there.

255
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:30,000
I know I thought about it, but I was sort of disconnected from campus and disconnected from other people.

256
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:36,000
A little later, the next year came the Freedom Rights.

257
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:42,000
And something very important to me was that there was a professor at Wesleyan

258
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:50,000
who had an instructor, actually, named John Maguire, who was a professor of McGuire,

259
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:53,000
was a religion teacher.

260
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:57,000
I was not one of his students, but several of the fellows in the fraternity were.

261
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:04,000
This was a pretty bright group of students, and not easy to impress.

262
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:10,000
And they were very impressed by Professor Maguire, who had come from Alabama.

263
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:16,000
He was a Yale Divinity, and then had been recruited to teach at Wesleyan, and then he did,

264
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:19,000
and went on to the career there for a while.

265
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:23,000
He wound up out here as President of the Plair and My Graduate School, and so on and so forth.

266
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:32,000
In any event, he received this we knew contemporarily, that he had received the phone call from his friend,

267
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:39,000
Rev. William Sloane Coffin Jr, that after the Anniston bus burned, which is in most high school

268
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:45,000
and college history books, survey books, and was all over the press.

269
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:53,000
First of the freedom riots, we said we have to try from here.

270
00:17:53,000 --> 00:17:55,000
It's a call of conscience.

271
00:17:55,000 --> 00:17:59,000
And John, I know, the call, and John, I know you have finally exams coming up.

272
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:03,000
It's a May of, and it's a first year teacher.

273
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:10,000
And there's a rather famous moment where in the world of the campus at Wesleyan, where he,

274
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:18,000
so I remember hearing it, and then later reading about it, a book by George George Plimpton + Jean Stein,

275
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:26,000
it was on the Robert F. Kennedy funeral train, and they interviewed people who were on the train in 1968.

276
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:36,000
But any of that captures the story there too, where John Maguire wanted to see the dean of the department,

277
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:43,000
the chair of the department, Dr. David Swift, and said, Dr. Swift, I know this is unusual, and I realize,

278
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:47,000
I know what I'm doing, but I have a call of conscience.

279
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:49,000
Conscience, I have a call of conscience.

280
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:55,000
Well, John Maguire had roamed at some conferences with Dr. Martin Luther King, also.

281
00:18:55,000 --> 00:18:58,000
And he's got to have a call of conscience.

282
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:08,000
And I know we've not finished the semester yet, but I'm going to join William Stone call for some other people

283
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:15,000
who knew how he even went down to New York and went to Freedom Rite, where upon David Swift stared at him for a minute,

284
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:23,000
and then he said, Dr. Swift, the department picked up the telephone and said, if it was wife, please pack my bags.

285
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:29,000
I've got some young foolish professor going out to Freedom Rites, I better come too.

286
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:31,000
So he did.

287
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:38,000
And without going too far into the details, Swift was a senior person around there, and as the saying goes,

288
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:49,000
when Swift went on the Freedom Ride. Wesley and went on the Freedom Rite, my roommate and I at the time, both on Walson I had both said to one another,

289
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:55,000
not knowing about the Maguire, the faculty to faculty, the student recruitment.

290
00:19:55,000 --> 00:20:05,000
We had said when the Anniston bus thing, that we were primed enough in this struggle to say, we want to go on the rides,

291
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:15,000
but literally the bus that pulled out before we could get ourselves there, we were not operational, it didn't happen.

292
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:29,000
But I know it's a, I don't just suspect, I know that I came to a subtle conclusion that when other opportunities would come up, I'd do my best to, in fact, get into this.

293
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:43,000
One thing about the Freedom Rides-and the genius of the Freedom Rites, it's not as widely articulated when the literature comes up and, but understood at the time,

294
00:20:43,000 --> 00:20:50,000
as I'll mention it now, and I don't speak as a participant in the Freedom Rides; I was not on the Freedom Rites of 1961.

295
00:20:50,000 --> 00:21:07,000
It was clearly interstate travel, and going from state to state, there was no question about it, that the Commerce Laws were clearly involved and that, therefore, that forced the issue.

296
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:20,000
And whoever, over at core, Congressional Qualities thought this up, assuming they also grasped that, which I think they did, and there had been earlier efforts in the 1940s to do this out at Cleveland in such a place.

297
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:36,000
Ohio, it was Istro-Coginius, and they went down. I then came out to, went on and graduated, this was the 61, the next year, 1962, and graduated.

298
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:51,000
And then decided, kind of an whim, to come west, to come to Los Angeles for a year, sunshine, play basketball, maybe play some tennis, and enjoy the beach and chase the young ladies.

299
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:57,000
The figure I go there for a year, and then go somewhere else, come out for a year, graduate school.

300
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:08,000
And it turned out I was admitted to graduate work here in some other places, I came out, my college roommate Bruce Corrill, and it was extremely helpful.

301
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:24,000
And we had, it was Bruce and Stephen S. Trott, who's now on the night circuit Court of Appeals, senior status, former Associate Attorney General in the Reagan Administration, former Chief Deputy District Attorney in Los Angeles, former United States Attorney.

302
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:38,000
He and Bruce Corrill, along with a man named Paul Cable, who's deceased, were the ones each separate times, were the ones who forced the issue in the fraternity.

303
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:45,000
We had had a precipitating clause that we'd break from the national if it affected anyone in terms of joining.

304
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:48,000
In other words, if it was a real issue, not a theoretical issue.

305
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:54,000
And it affected Stephen S. Trott and Bruce Corrill, and they said, if that clause is there, we're not joining.

306
00:22:54,000 --> 00:22:59,000
They had been educated to the issue, prepped for the issue, never anything else.

307
00:22:59,000 --> 00:23:08,000
And Bruce Corrill and Stephen S. Trott are two of the most remarkable of their lives, they're both mid-m I age, to the most remarkable individuals I've met.

308
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:10,000
It was here or this business?

309
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:14,000
It was at Wesley, and these were first-year college students.

310
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:21,000
Remember, I'm a year ahead of them, because I'd come in the year before, and they're also class of 62 fraternity brothers.

311
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:25,000
Trott, this is before your time and before your parents time, both of you.

312
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:34,000
But Stephen S. Trott went on to be one of the famous The Highwaymen, Michael Row the Boat Ashore, Michael Row the Boat Ashore, all at least, Trott.

313
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:37,000
So they figure into the story a little bit later in other ways.

314
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:42,000
I came out here for graduate school, and why don't I pause on that, you?

315
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:52,000
Okay, so let's just pick up there, we've got your ad to Los Angeles, and what graduate program did you enroll in?

316
00:23:52,000 --> 00:23:53,000
In history?

317
00:23:53,000 --> 00:23:54,000
In history.

318
00:23:54,000 --> 00:24:06,000
And I came west, and all seriousness, not only was it to chase the young ladies and play basketball on tennis, but I had done a paper, a long paper in my junior year.

319
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:20,000
I mean, been a way to call it, from college year came back, on the American Progressive Movement, one of the great historians of the Progressive Movement's professor George Mowry, who taught at UCLA.

320
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:29,000
And I arrived and found his seminar was filled.

321
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:35,000
What me being me, I marched into his office hours, and said, Professor Maurey, I came 3,000 miles to work with you.

322
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:38,000
I read every single thing you've written that's been published.

323
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:43,000
I went to Wesleyan," and he said, well, I think we can work you into the seminar.

324
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:46,000
And he was a wonderful man to me.

325
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:53,000
And he wanted to back at Chapel Hill, by the way.

326
00:24:53,000 --> 00:25:03,000
He had been a student, he had been very close to Frank Graham, when Frank Graham was, before Frank Graham became governor, or a senator for a while in North Carolina.

327
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:16,000
He had been a student of, he had been a professor for a while at Chapel Hill, and I want to be at UCLA after a couple of other stops and terrific man.

328
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:21,000
So I'm, but I don't know anyone to speak of in Los Angeles.

329
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:26,000
But I began to get acquainted with folks.

330
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:45,000
But I, in my case, what precipitated my engagement and all this directly was, I had been a long-wind trot, Stephen S. Trott, and helped bring the National Student Association to Wesleyan.

331
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:56,000
It was an idea Bob Patricelli had with Bob Ranford, a student body president, you know, Wesleyan to sort of get campus politics out of the sandbox and into a fuller engagement.

332
00:25:56,000 --> 00:26:02,000
And I had played some role there at a conference, a regional conference, and we made a report at Wesleyan.

333
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:05,000
I was somewhat informed on National Student Association.

334
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:30,000
I wrote a letter in support of NSA when I was at UCLA, probably a letter of that little consequence, no one knew me when it was defending NSA, with National Student Association when there had been a hostile editorial written in the campus newspaper, the Daily Browen, which, so I wrote, and I figured I better get over to the office and see, learned something about the men and women who are over in NSA on this chapter.

335
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:51,000
And I then met Steve McNichols. And Steve McNichols, who later that year in 1963, became the NSA rep, was active in NSA, and it turned out, and they thought of me as a fellow NSA, having had this background, and so on.

336
00:26:51,000 --> 00:27:06,000
I met a fellow named Steve Robbins, who became National President of NSA. This was the year before the CIA involvement with NSA, had been revealed by Mike Wood, and was a friend of Steve McNichols.

337
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:16,000
But Steve had done the freedom rides, in fact, from the West Coast. Part of the idea on the freedom rides was to try to fill the jails and to come in a pincer movement, West Coast, East Coast.

338
00:27:16,000 --> 00:27:44,000
And in the course of that, a couple of years earlier, not only had Steve McNichols and Bob Singleton, Helen Berry Singleton, Robert C. Farrell, and later with the City Councilman, Bob Singleton, and Los Angeles, and Steve, and then Helen, and Bob Singleton, Bob's going on to be a professor at Loyola Marymount, Helen Berry, Acta, and the Arts.

339
00:27:44,000 --> 00:28:00,000
They went, the Singleton's went on the Mississippi Freedom Ride and spent the jail time, prison time, and parchment, state put it, and Steve McNichols and Robert C. Farrell, he gone to the Houston rides.

340
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:14,000
And Steve McNichols have been very badly beaten, and in that ride, and if I could come out here as a very good tennis player, and it was going to forego that in the rest of his life.

341
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:27,000
But we saw each other and became acquainted. He did a very good job of bringing interesting speakers to the campus. He brought Chuck McDew, who was one of the heads of Snick, also brought Malcolm X.

342
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:43,000
It turned out we had hosted Malcolm X at Wesleyan, and it's spent a fair amount of time with him because at our fraternity, actually we had a tradition of having people, these small colleges, you do this, some have people for dinner, and so on and so forth, and really make a full day of it sometimes a weekend.

343
00:28:43,000 --> 00:28:52,000
I actually spent a fair amount of time together when I met him, and then here we are three or four months later after the summer, bam, and the fall, having seen him in the spring.

344
00:28:52,000 --> 00:29:07,000
See Malcolm X again, where they recognize each other, we chat, I explain, I'm now in graduate school out here following him around, and he laughed, he was relaxed about it, and he really indicated he was relaxed about it.

345
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:23,000
And then Lenna and Michael's brought in, had very strong building, civil rights consciousness, and staying connected, a little later with civil rights, had a civil rights division of an NSA.

346
00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:41,000
I then pick up an article by John Poppy, who had written for either Colliers or Look about the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee and the efforts of Sam Block and Charles McLaurin and Willie Willie Wazir Peacock to register voters in the Mississippi Delta.

347
00:29:41,000 --> 00:30:09,000
And it was quite a story, harrowing experiences, the segregationists trying to get them, it's a world of people not taking the man and then finding places to stay and registering voters, and people when they did try to register to vote, being cut off the welfare roles by the county governments, we're talking Leflore County, Tallahatchie County, and so on.

348
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:17,000
Either in the county or not far from the county where I'm at Tellham being killed in the 1955, this is eight years later.

349
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:32,000
And I read it, I removed by it, and thought about it, and then a good deal.

350
00:30:32,000 --> 00:31:01,000
And then all hell broke loose in Birmingham. In May of 1963, we're talking the academic year of 62-63. Fire hoses, and I'm not particularly a person, what it is of the television screen, but I was, by that time I'm with a family where I'm in effect helping take care of their kids on weekends and stuff.

351
00:31:01,000 --> 00:31:10,000
And then I'm with a family where I'm in the weekends and kind of a nanny figure, but that overstates it, but wonderful family.

352
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:29,000
And I had great admiration for both Norman Gabby Reskin, and Norman Reskin was something of a war hero who flew fighter planes over Nazi Germany, and his stories of him parachuting out in the marquee, helping him get out, getting him back across the channel, and flying more planes.

353
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:41,000
And I was a former RISK, Norman Reskin, terrific guy. It wasn't just his biography, it's kind of individually what he was, he's not deceased.

354
00:31:41,000 --> 00:31:57,000
And I said to him, keeping in mind this freedom rider business a couple of years earlier, I thought I had a teaching assistantship lined up, I had a resident assistantship lined up, I wasn't married.

355
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:10,000
I don't particularly important person in my life in that regard. I was eager, I wasn't particularly finding anyone willing. And furthermore, and I had no debt.

356
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:25,000
And it occurred to me if I'm ever going to be able to do something like this, now I know a lot about these things from my perspective.

357
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:35,000
I better do it. And I asked Norman about it, we sometimes have a graham crackers and milk that we got home, and I'm family talking it.

358
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:44,000
And I said, what do you think? He said, well, if I were, I have mortgage in a family and a business and everything else is ever to be in your situation, I'd do it.

359
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:59,000
And that's important to me, his views are important to me. It's still notional, but getting more of a live option, the John Poppy story.

360
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:12,000
I could cite that, practically quote that story right now. And then of course, the several days of bull Connor and the fire hoses and all the rest of it.

361
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:40,000
And I come across campus, I should add that there was a, she's not a public figure, so I just mentioned her name, the young lady. I was particularly interested in with whom I had shared my notions, my thoughts about this, this, there are gender components to these things.

362
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:53,000
I shared my thoughts about this particular article, the John Poppy piece, I had no, from time to time, I had no car from time to time, she gave me a ride home to this place I was staying and so on so forth. As terrific as a lady.

363
00:33:53,000 --> 00:34:05,000
So I am in the student, the, the Kirkoff Hall is where the student is right next to Akram and student union is really part of the student center area there.

364
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:21,000
And I am going to my mailbox to pick up the mail the next day or so after this conversation with Norm Raskett. And I bump into me, Nichols. And I say, Steve, I'm thinking of going down to help out with snack.

365
00:34:21,000 --> 00:34:35,000
I mentioned the John Poppy article, which he may have been the one to point out to me in the first place. It's possible. And I'm thinking of going down to Mississippi, make McNichols, says being Nichols, he says, well, terrific.

366
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:50,000
I said literally the words where I am thinking about right. He says, well, it turns out Sam Block and Charles McLaurin are going to be at the University of Religious Conference Center,

367
00:34:50,000 --> 00:35:06,000
which is right next to the UCLA campus. They're going to be there tonight. And I'm helping out on their visit. My briefs, he had just been elected. This is down the spring. He had just been elected to NSA rap, he had civil rights credentials in the first place.

368
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:30,000
And he said, we can arrange a ride. And as I open my mouth, the young lady walks up where upon Steve turns to her and says, Rick is going to Mississippi to help. And I said to myself, speaking of myself, I said, my man, it looks like you're going to Mississippi.

369
00:35:30,000 --> 00:35:49,000
So, I worked out. We made the arrangement. This is a world before cell phones and all the rest of it. But many of it somehow made Nichols prime these traps.

370
00:35:49,000 --> 00:36:10,000
I would meet them again. This was in, I guess, late morning or early afternoon. And rendezvous again with them at the URC around Steve at around five or so on six, thirty or seven. It was a conference on civil rights to tell the story of what they were doing.

371
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:30,000
And these fellas were, I've already been told about me and were agreeable to it. And then, and then, and then, the McNichols says, there's some people you need to meet. And in addition to that, I'm going to do this. And so with a mutual friend, a man named Paul Albert, Steve knew it was a graduate student.

372
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:39,000
He's a very active and progressive and liberal and left causes. Originally out of Ohio, mature more mature since his thirties.

373
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:57,000
Grand Student Sociology Department, we go over to a party in the Hollywood Hills upon the election of a man named George E. Brown Jr, who had just been elected to Congress.

374
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:13,000
Early in the 62 elections of 63 and very newly elected City Council Member Tom Bradley. And the group of which Steve, to which it's referring me and the people hosting the party.

375
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:23,000
I mean, a variety of people got involved hosting parties. But the core of this party was Californians for Liberal Representation. These days, we'd probably call it Californians for progressive representation.

376
00:37:23,000 --> 00:37:31,000
Which really quite a remarkable group of people, give an example. Two of Tom Bradley's first three deputy mayors came out of this The CLR-to-Bradley deputy-mayor pipeline.

377
00:37:31,000 --> 00:37:46,000
Some years later, they may come to this party and introduce me. And with the idea that Congressman Brown might be willing to write a letter that I could have with me.

378
00:37:46,000 --> 00:38:03,000
Saying I volunteer asked by him, written a letter, a letterhead observing voter registration practices in the South. The theory wasn't that it would do anything for me if I was in the hands of officials.

379
00:38:03,000 --> 00:38:16,000
But rather, if I was in a situation where my life was in danger from people who were not officials, who might hesitate if they thought in some way I was federal.

380
00:38:16,000 --> 00:38:29,000
And so George E. Brown Jr, who's rather remarkable man in puffing this cigar, is the whole UCLA connection. George E. Brown Jr. + Tom Bradley UCLA roommates and so on.

381
00:38:29,000 --> 00:38:42,000
And the co-op. And the puffing is a guard. And all the rest of it nodding, he agreed. And sure enough, a week or so later, I'm in Mississippi and this letter arrives. He did take care of it and sent it.

382
00:38:42,000 --> 00:39:05,000
And it made in some ways a bit helpful. Then I went with, so I went and stayed overnight. So let my folks know. I had the decency to my daughter pulls a stunt like this. I have a helper. But I'd call my folks and my mother remembers from Arkansas. She said, honey, not Mississippi.

383
00:39:05,000 --> 00:39:20,000
But I went, well, a couple of other places too, including parts of Arkansas. But that was her quick reaction. And so I went down with them and arrived in Greenwood.

384
00:39:20,000 --> 00:39:49,000
Did you ever been to Mississippi? When I arrived and showed up and it was a, you know, arrived three follows. We drove straight through. And Sam Block and Charles McLaurin really very remarkable, both African Americans, very remarkable organizers and leaders in their own way, even before the civil rights movement.

385
00:39:49,000 --> 00:40:18,000
Sam Block was a well-known popular musician. Sam Block's band was going around to lots of dances and parties tremendously well-known all through Mississippi and African American circles. And a real extraordinary follow. He passed away some years ago out here in Los Angeles. But he's originally a native Mississippi. So none of them. And I showed up. And one of the, and one of the,

386
00:40:18,000 --> 00:40:47,000
I was there for a bit of time and in Mississippi. And I remember, for example, going to church south of Greenwood, north of Canton, Mississippi, that small rural church and hearing and vivid terms, the Exodus story. And the promise land and getting to freedom and giving some sense of the world.

387
00:40:48,000 --> 00:41:15,000
And special resonance to that wonderful song, go down Moses way down in freedom land and so on. All done deep in the, deep in the curriculum of what Baptists describe as the Old Testament and very powerful linkages to what had happened to the Jewish people, the Hebrew people in the Exodus and in the book of Exodus.

388
00:41:15,000 --> 00:41:34,000
I can remember being going to a voter registration rally in the outskirts of Canton, Mississippi. And we're there. And about different people there about to have me say a few words. I was the white guy. I was the white person around.

389
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:59,000
This is the year before Mississippi freedom summer, 63. So I found myself sort of at this church and then about to do it here. So representing the fact that there are people who are allies that we care about in the north and in the west. You've got some port and so on and so forth. And I was careful to limit my remarks to a very few words.

390
00:41:59,000 --> 00:42:23,000
But when I did speak briefly, and I was ready to speak again at this baseball, baseball field rally over on the third base site. And Willie Willie Wazir Peacock walked over to me and said before I spoke and other said time to go. Just walk. And so I don't look.

391
00:42:23,000 --> 00:42:46,000
So we just walk towards cars and we got into cars and then I did take a peek coming around on the right field side on the first base side there. They were the Confederate flags flying, carload after carload after carload of guys and those cars and the crowd just it was late afternoon, dusk and early evening summertime.

392
00:42:46,000 --> 00:43:05,000
Dusk and people just feeding away that we drove out of there and got on the road and drove on until the night and got back safely. But it was got some idea of the menace and so on. A little later.

393
00:43:05,000 --> 00:43:12,000
I was going to ask you because you talked about driving with them across country to to me.

394
00:43:13,000 --> 00:43:25,000
I was going to ask him when you mentioned driving across country to Mississippi. Just being in a car, guys of different races, could be quite challenging to see what that was.

395
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:37,000
We drove through without any of it. We didn't particularly stop. We highballed. I mean we're all driving pretty fast across Texas and across the South West. We just kept, kind of we just rolled through.

396
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:48,000
There was no, we stopped. We rolled in at Greenwood. It was dark. It was late. It wasn't. People were still in the office. 708 Avenue in. I remember visiting it.

397
00:43:48,000 --> 00:44:00,000
After Rebecca and I married, we went back and visited it in 2008 just after the November election and went to that spot. You know how you remember certain addresses.

398
00:44:00,000 --> 00:44:17,000
And the buildings gone but the footprints there. The stoop on where a lot of serious discussions were held. This cement stoop is right there. Oh yeah, lots of this was. When I say the snake off, I should modify that right away.

399
00:44:17,000 --> 00:44:29,000
It was the Council of Federated Organizations, Kofo, which was SNCC and WACP Corps. And I may be leaving SNCC and WACP Corps SCLC.

400
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:39,000
I think everyone in the wisdom, I don't think it was this autumn, before I came along and my very minor figure anyway in that constellation of people.

401
00:44:39,000 --> 00:44:59,000
But we can have our differences in New York and Washington, maybe even in Atlanta and other places. But down there, it's so serious. We better have a combined effort. And so it was a COFO operation. Now as a practical matter, fair number of the people there were snake. But for example, the man named Dave Dennis came in one day and he was with CORE, and so on.

402
00:44:59,000 --> 00:45:23,000
And it didn't, I mean, everyone, it didn't, I mean, it may have been episodes of their places where these things were worked out. I wasn't there that long. But what I once era was consequential. I then moved me on to Georgia. But because I was literally bumped in, sleeping in the same bed with Lawrence, Lawrence Guyot.

403
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:43,000
And he was in charge of the office because Bob Moses was up in New England. And we got up. I remember it was kind of a house behind a house in Greenwood near the office.

404
00:45:43,000 --> 00:46:05,000
And we were there and it would overstated to call out a safe house. But it was a hard place to find. They go in and start looking for people in that area. I know we were there. Probably the law enforcement knew perfectly well where we were. But the point, but the other hand, we weren't violating any laws, at least in the immediate sense.

405
00:46:05,000 --> 00:46:29,000
And the, I remember, Lawrence Guyot got up and somehow it had a word that Mrs. Hamer had. You know, was he knew this when I was awakening. He got up before I did. So he had no cell phone. So he somehow maybe had been a phone in the location or someone came over to get him. And I didn't realize that.

406
00:46:29,000 --> 00:46:50,000
But he said to me as I woke up and rub my eyes over. He said, I'm going to go bail out Mrs. Hamer, friendly little Hamer and some young ladies who were arrested over in Winona. And he, I started to say worst to the effect of do you want me to come along. I can't remember if I actually utter the words or not, but he was out the door.

407
00:46:50,000 --> 00:47:11,000
And he drove over to get them. And we learned and did not come back right away, nor did they come with him. And we learned that when he arrived, they handcuffed him and beat the hack out on with baseball bats and broad daylight, little of a Sunday.

408
00:47:11,000 --> 00:47:28,000
Right near Baptist Church, just beat him up baseball really and his head was swollen. They threw him in jail. I wind over up over in the office, been in the office. And now in charge is Willie Wazir Peacock. It was in Oakland, Willie Wazir Peacock.

409
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:45,000
And so I put myself in it. It was Wally and me. And then there was some drop off an age. I'm 23 at the time. Wazir Wally's about my age. So was Gia. Me and I'm being here together.

410
00:47:45,000 --> 00:48:06,000
But you drop off pretty quickly to 19 year olds by Moses the way Sam Block was off somewhere else and so on. And I figure it's into it. So you do what you're asked to do. And so I did everything I'm saying I did right now. I did it the direction of Wally and we work very well together. And we essentially doing what he said.

411
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:35,000
Jats and Ian some brilliant ideas. One of which was we realized remember this is Mississippi in 1963. It's much closer to the Mississippi of 1955. I meant tell Mississippi of 1935 Mississippi of 1925 and so on. Then it was to Mississippi after after the Civil Rights Act, the Voting Act, much different.

412
00:48:35,000 --> 00:48:54,000
And it was no effect. No local law enforcement presence on the FBI, the local FBI director. I happen to pick up a local paper running for state legislator. All white, Lily White primary.

413
00:48:54,000 --> 00:49:05,000
And the bureau was not particularly interested in being involved in civil rights per se. There were much more interested in communist and the civil rights movement. So so far.

414
00:49:05,000 --> 00:49:21,000
Oh, yeah. And so we had so in any event. We call a clause sitting of the New York Times at the time and also Karl Fleming at Newsweek.

415
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:43,000
Well, we divided up calls and called and first called Julian Bond. Excuse me. I have this backwards. He called Julian Bond and he called these two reporters. That's what it was. And they may have called into us. I remember some conversation. But now that I think about it, it was through Julian, it was communications director for Stick.

416
00:49:43,000 --> 00:50:04,000
And seemed to be always available two in the morning, five in the morning at the middle of the day, Sunday through Sunday, you know, and so on and so forth. And very, very, very good at this because the main thing we had, the law enforcement, no particular federal president was some press interest.

417
00:50:04,000 --> 00:50:25,000
And these folks called and then was here. Well, he asked me to do the thing that's me to call man, go Revers to see about another referee bail money. So I call Medgar Evers, who says, well, I remember worst of the fact of what Mr. Tuttle I will.

418
00:50:25,000 --> 00:50:49,000
I have to go out now to a meeting. I'll call you when I get back. I'm just going out the door is very and he probably was thinking to himself as he reached for both of his kids and reach for a lot of door to go to his home. Well, I've got to call that follow back and up in the greenwood because of Fannie Lou Hamer and so and so forth. And it was then that by Randela back with murder.

419
00:50:49,000 --> 00:50:59,000
So we then we and all hell breaks loose in Jackson.

420
00:50:59,000 --> 00:51:16,000
That grabbers had become a major regional figure and some largely a national figure because he had been the voice of Mississippi, African Americans and the Tillbys, Emmett Till case, been NAACP director, etc.

421
00:51:16,000 --> 00:51:28,000
And I miss Mississippi on the ground right in the heart of extremely dangerous and difficult plays in the murder.

422
00:51:28,000 --> 00:51:45,000
Willie Willie Wazir Peacock gets another idea that we can't find or we don't think we can't seem to find where Fannie Lou Hamer are, the young ladies, June Johnson, the others who are weathered.

423
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:54,000
And now Gia and the danger was the thing we were worried about is there being moved around. Then every once responsible, no one responsible.

424
00:51:54,000 --> 00:52:02,000
You wind up, people are dead and missing and now I'm sorry, and a jury can't decide, and DAs can't decide who to file against and so on.

425
00:52:02,000 --> 00:52:14,000
I'm talking about including well-meaning people. The whole thing because the underlying structure and the chances are in a segregated, all lily white situation, you're going to get people to simply want this stuff excused and go on in life as usual.

426
00:52:15,000 --> 00:52:24,000
So it's very, very dangerous. It turned out they were in the jail the whole time. We just didn't know it.

427
00:52:24,000 --> 00:52:40,000
And we couldn't find it and the usual sources of information for one reason, other dried up. It was pretty good underground because generally white folks down there in that setting didn't realize that African Americans, at least is what we thought, could understand what they were saying and so on.

428
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:49,000
But that got shut down in which that itself was concerning, the normal conversation in front of people and so on and so forth.

429
00:52:49,000 --> 00:53:08,000
So let me be gone suggested I call the governor. So I did. And we scripted and he scripted me. I explained just who I was. I'm quite new here. I'm a, I'm a, you see, I like graduate student from California. I'm here helping in the civil rights effort here.

430
00:53:08,000 --> 00:53:24,000
He took the call. I went to when governor took the call and I said just what I said and said that we, I mean, go back a step after Medgar Evers died. All I started to say all hell broke loose in Jackson.

431
00:53:24,000 --> 00:53:34,000
And that's the famous moment when John door or iconic moment goes down the, comes down the street holding up his credentials saying, I am John door from the United States Department of Justice.

432
00:53:34,000 --> 00:53:53,000
So the, it's interesting because Medgar Evers in two ways, one I'll get to perhaps a little later, even in death continued to play a helpful role in the civil rights moment.

433
00:53:53,000 --> 00:54:05,000
And in this case, in case of business hammer and the others as well, I pick out and I said to each other a year or so ago, we're talking about this. That's basically doing what we said. We kept them alive.

434
00:54:05,000 --> 00:54:21,000
And it's again, it's hard to remember this, but people would disappear. There were people being shot. And for example, in the mega ever saying Mr. Deela back with didn't bother to wipe off his prints. He just put down the rifle went on about his business.

435
00:54:21,000 --> 00:54:34,000
There were all sorts of stories about this. There was no legal remedy here and nothing. So in any event, we weren't sure what was going to happen there.

436
00:54:34,000 --> 00:54:46,000
What did happen is they were being badly beaten and brutalized in the jail. They forced trustees, African American trustees, our prisoners to beat them.

437
00:54:46,000 --> 00:55:04,000
So it's over. None of that. I did what exactly what Willie Willie Wazir Peacock suggested I called and did say to them, look, I'm here. I'm from who I am. I give them my name. Probably a wiretapper on here somewhere on this. And I'm probably more than one.

438
00:55:04,000 --> 00:55:28,000
And we know that you've got your hands fall in Jackson. They pulled in everything. Fishing game wardens, highway patrol, everything they had because of these demonstrations, which were where Jackson was teetering on the edge of even more serious problem.

439
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:48,000
I said, what I can report to you is that if Mrs. Hamer and Lawrence Guyot and the others in their names and Annelle Ponder, June Jackson, a couple other people, if we're not notified where they are and how they can be, their release can be secured, there will be major demonstrations up here in the Delta. You're in Greenwood.

440
00:55:48,000 --> 00:56:01,000
And so, parenthesis, he knew what I knew, what Dick Gregory had come out some months earlier and actually had been public activities around the civil rights in Greenwood.

441
00:56:01,000 --> 00:56:15,000
And so the governor said to me, well, son, are you threatening me? I said, sir, I'm not threatening you. I'm new here. I'm simply reporting to you. I'm reporting what I'm told and I'm asked to call you. No, I'm not. I'm just telling you what's going to happen.

442
00:56:15,000 --> 00:56:26,000
And I'll never know, probably never know for sure. Maybe you folks will find out as you go along or it'll become evident in some way or other.

443
00:56:26,000 --> 00:56:44,000
But we had a timeline, a deadline on this. We need to know by such and such a time is later that day. And before that deadline, a couple hours later, the highway patrol, which last time I looked reports to the governor of state, highway patrol, called and indicated where they were.

444
00:56:44,000 --> 00:57:01,000
They were at the jail. So, where we could go and get them bailed out. Andrew Young flew in. Andrew Young actually drove in. He had been at a conference. I think probably in Alabama and Burmiham. This I picked up from talking with him about it years, years, years later.

445
00:57:01,000 --> 00:57:27,000
He came in and with bail money to go get them out. And I still remember this very tough situation. I know. And I still remember thinking the 23rd song that goes through the valley of the shadow of death as he, understanding everything got in car and drove over to.

446
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:39,000
I know and have to bail them out. And he has a whole story he tells about getting them out and he did and brought them back.

447
00:57:39,000 --> 00:57:56,000
Meanwhile, word reached through this network. I'll use the term underground through reliable sources that Mr. Byron De La Beckwith, who was from Greenwood, which is where the co-fall off as well.

448
00:57:56,000 --> 00:58:16,000
And it demonstrated his willingness and his capacity to do murder so that he was going to go kill the white boy. I was at white boy. So they realized that danger. And so they put me under a blanket after half a day, I guess, of discussing it.

449
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:35,000
And took me to Memphis, the airport, and flew to the SNCC office in Atlanta. And went in there. It's from there.

450
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:51,000
SNCC was, I went on to Chatham County, I went on to Savannah, but when I was in Atlanta, SNCC was always to its great credit pushing in those days, pushing the envelope.

451
00:58:51,000 --> 00:59:11,000
And we've been a settlement reached by the Civil Rights organizations and the Atlanta authorities taking it easy in Atlanta on various civil rights activities, particularly lunch counter sit-ins and so on and so forth.

452
00:59:11,000 --> 00:59:29,000
SNCC wasn't necessarily always part of that consensus. And so I was part of a group. I remember one day walking down to desegregate a lunch counter. I remember passing by, it was some distance.

453
00:59:29,000 --> 00:59:50,000
I'd say a 40-50 yards away, but I had a clear line. I could see Lester Maddox out in front of his restaurant and he had a pickaxe handle. And he was out there. I don't remember if it was his emblem. I don't remember him specifically having the pickaxe handle, but I remember him having a visible figure pointing and gesturing and so on and so forth.

454
00:59:50,000 --> 01:00:14,000
When I'm by to another restaurant and I remember we were at sit-in there and this is just a straight forward restaurant sit-in desegregation standing on the shoulders of the sit-ins in 1960.

455
01:00:14,000 --> 01:00:31,000
And there we were. It was, remember, it was all before the 1964 Public Accommodation Act, Civil Rights Act. And I still remember pretty vivid in my mind. There's a line of black and white were there.

456
01:00:31,000 --> 01:00:59,000
We're in Atlanta, not in Mississippi and not in rural Georgia. And a lady had this waitress who was so upset. Her whole world was being turned upside down. And she had this back of absolute boiling water.

457
01:00:59,000 --> 01:01:16,000
And she was standing, I mean, lunch counter. And she's right here and she's above me, standing above me. I'm in my head's here and she's here with that lunch box. And there were African American here, African American here, white person here. She's standing right there.

458
01:01:16,000 --> 01:01:39,000
And I looked at her and she was looking at me and she was extremely upset. Behind us were some reporters. And one of whom I'd run into, I'd gone to Wesleyan, he was a graduated Hosea Williams. Just that's bringing us in.

459
01:01:39,000 --> 01:01:57,000
And he was named as John Kifner. And John Kifner was covering the Civil Rights Movement for the Berkshire Eagle, which is Berkshire, the Western Madison. And he later went on to a very distinguished guru with the New York Times.

460
01:01:57,000 --> 01:02:08,000
As widely known as a reporter's reporter, we're talking Beirut, we're talking the Fred Hampton killing in Chicago on and on and on.

461
01:02:08,000 --> 01:02:22,000
But he's standing there with us. I might back to him. So I take it. He was standing there with us. No pad and others. And it was a very long 45 seconds.

462
01:02:22,000 --> 01:02:41,000
A voice at the far end said, all right, and he called her by name. All right, he said, now let's all settle down. And that police officer walked in, had a wrapped his, his baton down, turned to our picket captain and her. She stepped, gave her, she stepped back.

463
01:02:41,000 --> 01:02:56,000
And he, he officer doing his duty. And he came in and he turned to whoever was in charge of us. And then there was a moment or two. Okay, do we? I, I wasn't in the command of this. I was doing what we wanted to do.

464
01:02:56,000 --> 01:03:07,000
But I take it was not a day we were going to go to jail and take an arrest. And so we moved on and left. As we walk back, John Kifner said to me,

465
01:03:07,000 --> 01:03:22,000
I'm going to put away my notepad. I'm going to join this effort. No, excuse me. That's not what happened. As we walked back, we talked about it. Wesleyan and William, small colleges, common ground, and so on.

466
01:03:22,000 --> 01:03:29,000
When I'm back, very shortly thereafter, that conversation did not happen that way it happened in another place.

467
01:03:29,000 --> 01:03:46,000
Went back to the SNCC office and there were marches going on in Chatham County, Savannah. And they, and the people in the SNCC office in Atlanta, one of whom was Casey Hayden.

468
01:03:46,000 --> 01:04:04,000
Another of whom was Dicky Romley. Casey Hayden for sure. And I think Dicky Romley was the other. Talk to, to me, to Bruce Gordon, who might have met. I've been there a few days.

469
01:04:04,000 --> 01:04:19,000
And also a man named Youngman, named Joe Iyer, who was 19 or so a student at Haverford College. Bruce was 23, Bruce's a year or so younger.

470
01:04:19,000 --> 01:04:33,000
I've been in the military, not a little time at, I think CCNY. And then at, you know, more house or more sprouts, setting theater, but it would join the movement, African American.

471
01:04:33,000 --> 01:04:48,000
And we had gotten acquainted in those few days around Atlanta and in size, so some and so on and so forth. And I said, what I like to say, you folks down to three of you down to Savannah.

472
01:04:48,000 --> 01:05:04,000
There's a Southern Christian Leadership Conference of Philly at the Chatham County Crusade for voters, which has been carrying on demonstrations, Hosea Hosea Williams, the Hosea Hosea Williams, and Benjamin Van Clark, the very charismatic folks.

473
01:05:04,000 --> 01:05:12,000
We think you folks might be able to help there, help them with some non-violent work and also just be supportive in various ways.

474
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:24,000
So we drove from Atlanta, one of these things you do it to do it, you just go do it. So we drive down to Savannah, Bruce Gordon and Joe Iyer.

475
01:05:24,000 --> 01:05:38,000
And so we drove down there and I remember we arrived at night, there at church in Savannah. And a place was packed. And they have been doing these night marches.

476
01:05:38,000 --> 01:05:50,000
This is for desecrification of the public facilities, me, restaurants, hotels, the desoto hotel there and other things, employment issues, so on.

477
01:05:50,000 --> 01:06:06,000
The voter registration was more than most places. I'm not saying it was as good as it should have been, but the Chatham County Crusade for voters actually Mr. Hosea Williams,

478
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:18,000
life had run for a county commission, I believe it was. And that was an electoral campaign a year or two earlier, hence the Chatham County Crusade for voters.

479
01:06:18,000 --> 01:06:34,000
They were some variants for the NAACP chapter there, which is working in its own manner. But Hosea Hosea Williams and Benjamin Van Clark and others were,

480
01:06:34,000 --> 01:06:49,000
had mobilized very major night marches. So we arrived and here's this walk in and there's this spellbinding oratory from Reverend, he became a Reverend, Reverend Hosea Williams,

481
01:06:49,000 --> 01:07:08,000
a chemist of the agricultural department, World War II, badly wounded, left for dead, came back and was beaten up as a serviceman, one of these servicemen in the 40s, 1945ers, beaten up coming off a train or bus upon returning to service, etc.

482
01:07:08,000 --> 01:07:27,000
But anyway, a remarkable man and he had gotten his college degrees at one of the Atlanta colleges and the child of a man named Blind Tom and another lady, and just a remarkable guy, terrific individual and children and so on and so forth.

483
01:07:27,000 --> 01:07:39,000
But worked for the U.S. government and the chemist and department, and Benjamin Van Clark, who was a terrific, recently out of high school student leader.

484
01:07:39,000 --> 01:07:50,000
I still remember the scenes when it was more than once, but that night was the first time I saw it. I said, all right, now we're about to go on on the march and we all know what will happen.

485
01:07:50,000 --> 01:08:01,000
In terms of discrediting us, if weapons were found on anyone, so please put your things in these baskets, they pass you on these baskets.

486
01:08:01,000 --> 01:08:08,000
And there was the clatter and clink of brass knuckles and sappers, oh god, I don't know how I've switched blades.

487
01:08:08,000 --> 01:08:11,000
But think of the political consciousness that time.

488
01:08:11,000 --> 01:08:16,000
Think of the commitment to sober rights and what that meant, but they were willing to do.

489
01:08:16,000 --> 01:08:26,000
And people were willing to forego that normal things that one carries and self-defense and so on and so forth.

490
01:08:27,000 --> 01:08:34,000
And so off we go on the marches and we're quite off, quite regularly.

491
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:40,000
And mass, what are called mass meetings in these churches.

492
01:08:40,000 --> 01:08:46,000
And we go on to, we stay at a place we go upstairs.

493
01:08:46,000 --> 01:08:51,000
I didn't particularly notice the person I did to where we're staying.

494
01:08:51,000 --> 01:08:55,000
And then Donna, I mean, the place we're staying is a house of prostitution.

495
01:08:55,000 --> 01:09:00,000
And it's something that I've thought about a good deal since.

496
01:09:00,000 --> 01:09:02,000
And that is what you have, the ladies were there.

497
01:09:02,000 --> 01:09:06,000
They knew who we were, the we acknowledge each other.

498
01:09:06,000 --> 01:09:09,000
They see them and we're upstairs.

499
01:09:09,000 --> 01:09:13,000
But this was a pro bono thing.

500
01:09:13,000 --> 01:09:17,000
The owners were doing this as part of the movement.

501
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:24,000
And furthermore, on occasion, we're actually putting their places of business up his bail money.

502
01:09:25,000 --> 01:09:27,000
Risking them.

503
01:09:27,000 --> 01:09:32,000
It's really quite remarkable to think about it a bit.

504
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:45,000
And the, after, so after a few days of marching, one of the most darnful things I've done or agreed to do,

505
01:09:45,000 --> 01:09:52,000
is they came to me, the leadership came to me, Benjamin Van Clark, who said, well Rick, remember I've been out there marching.

506
01:09:52,000 --> 01:09:55,000
And one of two or three whites.

507
01:09:55,000 --> 01:09:58,000
And one of two to be literal about it.

508
01:09:58,000 --> 01:10:01,000
And these marches are all kinds of cameras.

509
01:10:01,000 --> 01:10:04,000
All those public marches.

510
01:10:04,000 --> 01:10:08,000
And click, click, click, like eyes or locales from the flash bulbs and so on.

511
01:10:08,000 --> 01:10:12,000
And this are that journalist security people, others.

512
01:10:12,000 --> 01:10:15,000
And plus, these people found it interesting.

513
01:10:15,000 --> 01:10:17,000
So there we are.

514
01:10:17,000 --> 01:10:21,000
And they say, well, we're going to have you engage quarters away from here.

515
01:10:21,000 --> 01:10:26,000
And we're going to go to white supremacist meetings, to public meetings.

516
01:10:26,000 --> 01:10:29,000
So I go and agree to it.

517
01:10:29,000 --> 01:10:33,000
And I get a place to stay.

518
01:10:33,000 --> 01:10:36,000
And you have some questions, what do you do during the day?

519
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:38,000
I mean, what do you do at your time?

520
01:10:38,000 --> 01:10:40,000
I saw by by Birdie.

521
01:10:40,000 --> 01:10:41,000
So often.

522
01:10:41,000 --> 01:10:43,000
