01:42:31,000 --> 01:42:39,000
And they, well, then we went to Mr. Aaron Buchsbaum, Aaron Buchsbaum,

987
01:42:39,000 --> 01:42:50,000
and Mr. Waxler, and whether I was here, went to another judge in Savannah,

988
01:42:50,000 --> 01:42:58,000
who made the rulings we had hoped for, and also,

989
01:42:58,000 --> 01:43:07,000
and then, also, there was also part of a package that arranged that the others also got out of J. Ellis,

990
01:43:07,000 --> 01:43:13,000
while they went back in. His name was, I think of the court's name in a minute.

991
01:43:13,000 --> 01:43:18,000
He was very nice. He saw me, he was a native of Savannah,

992
01:43:18,000 --> 01:43:24,000
and he said to me after the proceedings, after he'd ordered my release, Dr. Waxler's,

993
01:43:24,000 --> 01:43:30,000
or was there to provide his property bond. He took me aside and said,

994
01:43:30,000 --> 01:43:34,000
I'm sorry about all this, what's happened. He didn't have to say that to me.

995
01:43:34,000 --> 01:43:38,000
It was very, very nice of him to say it. The others got out,

996
01:43:38,000 --> 01:43:42,000
and I, meanwhile, went back up north, I was part of the deal, am I getting out,

997
01:43:42,000 --> 01:43:47,000
that I would leave the area, and I would risk his property,

998
01:43:47,000 --> 01:43:51,000
because Judge Mullen would go after it. Oh, yeah, I could risk his math.

999
01:43:51,000 --> 01:43:56,000
I gave my word, that I would not cause any trouble in Savannah, and it was over.

1000
01:43:56,000 --> 01:44:04,000
It was September, early September. I came back up north, and everyone got out.

1001
01:44:04,000 --> 01:44:06,000
In jail, not only a bit of...

1002
01:44:06,000 --> 01:44:08,000
What was the original charge?

1003
01:44:08,000 --> 01:44:12,000
It was these seven-piece bonds. That was in her, each of us,

1004
01:44:12,000 --> 01:44:15,000
that we had disturbed the peace under a Georgia statute,

1005
01:44:15,000 --> 01:44:22,000
disturbed the peace of the people who had sworn out these.

1006
01:44:22,000 --> 01:44:27,000
Apparently, Judge Mullen had made no secret of it. He invited this procedure.

1007
01:44:27,000 --> 01:44:33,000
As he saw it from his point of view, he was quieting things down,

1008
01:44:33,000 --> 01:44:40,000
and took this on. Savannah, standing on the shoulders of what happened,

1009
01:44:40,000 --> 01:44:44,000
because Jose Winslow's now out, had been out for a while.

1010
01:44:44,000 --> 01:44:52,000
Through a variety of techniques, before the Suburite Sack passed,

1011
01:44:52,000 --> 01:44:56,000
Savannah became the first city in the South to desegregate.

1012
01:44:56,000 --> 01:44:59,000
They had a biracial committee, everything else.

1013
01:44:59,000 --> 01:45:02,000
I also want to be clear and fair about this.

1014
01:45:02,000 --> 01:45:05,000
The mayor of Savannah Malcolm Maclean, was widely regarded as a moderate.

1015
01:45:05,000 --> 01:45:11,000
He had beaten the other faction sometime earlier, but the other thing

1016
01:45:11,000 --> 01:45:19,000
is that it's important to say this, and that is in the context of my being in custody

1017
01:45:19,000 --> 01:45:22,000
in the Chatham County, jail, the comments of that follow-not,

1018
01:45:22,000 --> 01:45:25,000
was standing about his brother being in the clan and so on and so forth.

1019
01:45:25,000 --> 01:45:30,000
I got a good deal of negative attitude from some people.

1020
01:45:30,000 --> 01:45:34,000
There were some of the guards who were okay.

1021
01:45:34,000 --> 01:45:41,000
And there were two things I saw that in embryos,

1022
01:45:41,000 --> 01:45:43,000
he suggested some shift of attitude.

1023
01:45:43,000 --> 01:45:46,000
One was the reaction to these freedom schools,

1024
01:45:46,000 --> 01:45:54,000
where you could sense it even among the more hard-line guards of a look of a kind of respect.

1025
01:45:54,000 --> 01:45:57,000
There was a second thing that happened.

1026
01:45:57,000 --> 01:45:59,000
I was in custody.

1027
01:45:59,000 --> 01:46:01,000
I was there for a month and a half.

1028
01:46:01,000 --> 01:46:05,000
And I was in custody when the March on Washington took place.

1029
01:46:05,000 --> 01:46:08,000
But we could hear it upstairs on the third floor.

1030
01:46:08,000 --> 01:46:11,000
We could hear the television. We could hear it. We couldn't see it.

1031
01:46:11,000 --> 01:46:16,000
And I was released a few days later, but in September.

1032
01:46:16,000 --> 01:46:22,000
But I detected a shift on the part of everybody

1033
01:46:22,000 --> 01:46:25,000
because after the March on Washington,

1034
01:46:25,000 --> 01:46:35,000
there was some recognition began to settle in that the civil rights side might win.

1035
01:46:35,000 --> 01:46:39,000
It might get civil rights legislation passed.

1036
01:46:39,000 --> 01:46:52,000
There certainly no great grounds for hope for quite a considerable period of time.

1037
01:46:52,000 --> 01:46:55,000
Things were pretty modeled up and everything else.

1038
01:46:55,000 --> 01:46:58,000
But that was important. That March was important.

1039
01:46:58,000 --> 01:47:00,000
Back to Mr. Evers for a minute,

1040
01:47:00,000 --> 01:47:02,000
without making too much of this point,

1041
01:47:02,000 --> 01:47:04,000
even in death,

1042
01:47:04,000 --> 01:47:10,000
Magga Evers was helpful in terms of the release of the governor of Barnett Funkall.

1043
01:47:10,000 --> 01:47:14,000
We know you got your hands full in Jackson.

1044
01:47:14,000 --> 01:47:20,000
And we're prepared or I can report to you that there will be demonstrations here in Greenwood

1045
01:47:20,000 --> 01:47:24,000
and have someone bonus, and so on.

1046
01:47:24,000 --> 01:47:27,000
And the other thing was, I've always felt this,

1047
01:47:27,000 --> 01:47:31,000
that when I went over to Atlanta,

1048
01:47:31,000 --> 01:47:33,000
one of the things we did a day or so after,

1049
01:47:33,000 --> 01:47:35,000
they got me out,

1050
01:47:35,000 --> 01:47:41,000
is we all went down to the train station and organized crowds to come down and gather people

1051
01:47:41,000 --> 01:47:46,000
as the funeral train of Magga Revers came through.

1052
01:47:46,000 --> 01:47:52,000
And I think one of the ways in which the March on Washington, I'm stretching a point,

1053
01:47:52,000 --> 01:47:54,000
but I'm going to go and say it because I've over the past few years,

1054
01:47:54,000 --> 01:47:57,000
one of the things that helped make the March so successful,

1055
01:47:57,000 --> 01:47:59,000
where people came in from all over the country,

1056
01:47:59,000 --> 01:48:01,000
including coming up from the South.

1057
01:48:01,000 --> 01:48:02,000
Some came in from California,

1058
01:48:02,000 --> 01:48:07,000
but most people came in the Eastern time zones in the South and North,

1059
01:48:07,000 --> 01:48:15,000
as people began to help to create the organizational structures

1060
01:48:15,000 --> 01:48:17,000
and the relationships in the context.

1061
01:48:17,000 --> 01:48:23,000
It's all before Twitter and all before email and all before cell phones and everything else,

1062
01:48:23,000 --> 01:48:30,000
but the relationships to gather on this funeral cartage going up to Washington,

1063
01:48:30,000 --> 01:48:33,000
the relationships that were rather shortly afterwards,

1064
01:48:33,000 --> 01:48:38,000
those same networks would have been deployed to gather people to Carpool,

1065
01:48:38,000 --> 01:48:43,000
get on trains, buses, and poor into Washington for the March.

1066
01:48:43,000 --> 01:48:47,000
And I've always felt that I've never mentioned it to Mrs. Evers,

1067
01:48:47,000 --> 01:48:50,000
but it occurs that I'm going to send her a letter because the 50th is coming up,

1068
01:48:50,000 --> 01:48:53,000
then to send her a letter to capture them.

1069
01:48:53,000 --> 01:48:55,000
And any of them, and I came back out to California,

1070
01:48:55,000 --> 01:48:59,000
and then we remained involved in some things.

1071
01:48:59,000 --> 01:49:02,000
Why don't I pause for a minute and give you a chance to?

1072
01:49:02,000 --> 01:49:05,000
We'll probably take a second to close the file.

1073
01:49:05,000 --> 01:49:09,000
We'll probably start to wind down, but maybe towards that end,

1074
01:49:09,000 --> 01:49:12,000
as you're starting to tell us a little bit about what you did then,

1075
01:49:12,000 --> 01:49:13,000
or what was...

1076
01:49:13,000 --> 01:49:22,000
Well, I came back out here, and one of my better decisions that I made when I got back

1077
01:49:22,000 --> 01:49:26,000
was not to become one of these people that was sitting around the college campus

1078
01:49:26,000 --> 01:49:29,000
and endlessly tell these stories.

1079
01:49:29,000 --> 01:49:34,000
I've told them the SNCC conference, but it was Rebecca,

1080
01:49:34,000 --> 01:49:39,000
I passed away, and then I was able to get Rebecca to marry me,

1081
01:49:40,000 --> 01:49:46,000
who after we married in 2008, we went back to the Civil Rights sites,

1082
01:49:46,000 --> 01:49:50,000
went back to Winona, Mississippi, which I never visited,

1083
01:49:50,000 --> 01:49:53,000
but certainly had been engaged with Savannah,

1084
01:49:53,000 --> 01:49:56,000
I mean to Greenwood, went down to Canton, Mississippi,

1085
01:49:56,000 --> 01:50:02,000
and then I, family in Mississippi, went to visit them near Philadelphia, Mississippi,

1086
01:50:02,000 --> 01:50:07,000
and then went across the South to Savannah,

1087
01:50:07,000 --> 01:50:10,000
and actually saw the jail cell where I had been,

1088
01:50:10,000 --> 01:50:13,000
because that's now part of (former) Chatham County Jail, Savannah GA.

1089
01:50:13,000 --> 01:50:17,000
And they, you can look in, and these are all artists,

1090
01:50:17,000 --> 01:50:21,000
I actually saw the place I was, and then we went over to Atlanta,

1091
01:50:21,000 --> 01:50:28,000
and arrived by coincidence in the coincidence

1092
01:50:28,000 --> 01:50:31,000
at opening of the Joseo Hosea Williams collection.

1093
01:50:31,000 --> 01:50:37,000
He is a library at the library in Atlanta,

1094
01:50:37,000 --> 01:50:39,000
whose name will come back to me in a minute,

1095
01:50:39,000 --> 01:50:43,000
so well known, predominantly African American collections.

1096
01:50:43,000 --> 01:50:46,000
And it's on tip of my tongue.

1097
01:50:46,000 --> 01:50:49,000
And any of it, his family, those of his remaining family members

1098
01:50:49,000 --> 01:50:51,000
were there as children, as a little coincidence.

1099
01:50:51,000 --> 01:50:56,000
When we were in Savannah, we arrived, and early before coming across,

1100
01:50:56,000 --> 01:51:05,000
and it turned out that there was a pictorial collection of Savannah

1101
01:51:05,000 --> 01:51:11,000
that, that summer of 63, and Aaron, Mr. Aaron Buchsbaum,

1102
01:51:11,000 --> 01:51:14,000
and his lovely wife Astor, were available for dinner,

1103
01:51:14,000 --> 01:51:19,000
and it turned out they told us that the, there was this exhibit

1104
01:51:19,000 --> 01:51:22,000
showing at Telfair Museum.

1105
01:51:22,000 --> 01:51:24,000
It was, I think, sponsored by the University of Georgia.

1106
01:51:24,000 --> 01:51:28,000
We went, we walked in, and there are pictures from that summer,

1107
01:51:28,000 --> 01:51:32,000
from those marches, but Benjamin Van Clark, and Trash Brownlee,

1108
01:51:32,000 --> 01:51:35,000
and Joseo Hosea Williams, and so on, and there were several quotes up,

1109
01:51:35,000 --> 01:51:38,000
and there were two quotes from Rick Tuttle,

1110
01:51:38,000 --> 01:51:40,000
which probably, for almost anyone in Georgia,

1111
01:51:40,000 --> 01:51:43,000
would raise a perfectly natural question of who is Rick Tottel.

1112
01:51:43,000 --> 01:51:47,000
But there I was, it was really quite a, there's a book out on this now,

1113
01:51:47,000 --> 01:51:53,000
I have very, very well-appointed book.

1114
01:51:53,000 --> 01:51:58,000
One of the interesting moments in my life, we were in Greenwood,

1115
01:51:58,000 --> 01:52:04,000
and at 708 Avenue N, Greenwood Mississippi, and at that moment,

1116
01:52:04,000 --> 01:52:14,000
I realized how little we've done in terms of dealing with truly deep poverty

1117
01:52:14,000 --> 01:52:17,000
in the North American United States.

1118
01:52:17,000 --> 01:52:21,000
One of the more moving moments I had a few minutes later,

1119
01:52:21,000 --> 01:52:27,000
after leaving the place where the COFO (Council of Federated Organizations) office had been,

1120
01:52:27,000 --> 01:52:31,000
where I'd been when I went to Mississippi, we went to a store,

1121
01:52:31,000 --> 01:52:34,000
are we looking around for people of an age where they might,

1122
01:52:34,000 --> 01:52:37,000
you know, have some memories together, and spend some time together,

1123
01:52:37,000 --> 01:52:41,000
and some workmen pointed this in the direction of a store or blocker.

1124
01:52:41,000 --> 01:52:44,000
So, away, we went over to the store, and as we pulled up,

1125
01:52:44,000 --> 01:52:48,000
we were driving a rental car, good looking black rental car.

1126
01:52:48,000 --> 01:52:51,000
It's about five years ago, I hopped on on one side,

1127
01:52:51,000 --> 01:52:56,000
and we're back up looking very fit, hopped on on the other,

1128
01:52:56,000 --> 01:53:02,000
and it probably was hard to tell just exactly who we were,

1129
01:53:02,000 --> 01:53:05,000
but there's always a possible, who knows who we were.

1130
01:53:05,000 --> 01:53:08,000
We come popping out on the car, and there's a group of young men

1131
01:53:09,000 --> 01:53:12,000
and African American young men on the corner,

1132
01:53:12,000 --> 01:53:17,000
and they begin to move away from it very carefully.

1133
01:53:17,000 --> 01:53:20,000
They don't know who we are, what we're doing.

1134
01:53:20,000 --> 01:53:24,000
We walked into the store, and it turned out it was a lady there

1135
01:53:24,000 --> 01:53:28,000
who had been around. She'd been a young lady,

1136
01:53:28,000 --> 01:53:32,000
14, 15-year-old lady, around the COFO (Council of Federated Organizations) office, the SNCC office.

1137
01:53:32,000 --> 01:53:35,000
And the next thing we were all singing,

1138
01:53:35,000 --> 01:53:38,000
was a little bit of a white song, as her sister was there,

1139
01:53:38,000 --> 01:53:41,000
someone else in this little general store.

1140
01:53:41,000 --> 01:53:45,000
And a couple of the fellows who've been outside came in

1141
01:53:45,000 --> 01:53:50,000
to buy a cigarette, you know, buy one cigarette at a time,

1142
01:53:50,000 --> 01:53:53,000
and they get the picture.

1143
01:53:53,000 --> 01:53:57,000
And when we walked out, the warmth of their receptions,

1144
01:53:57,000 --> 01:54:02,000
weren't the most moving experience that I've had ever.

1145
01:54:03,000 --> 01:54:09,000
But back to 1963, came out, and what happens a little later,

1146
01:54:09,000 --> 01:54:13,000
is we form a group on UCLA campus,

1147
01:54:13,000 --> 01:54:16,000
and near the religious conference center of the YMCA,

1148
01:54:16,000 --> 01:54:18,000
the Student Coordinating Committee,

1149
01:54:18,000 --> 01:54:21,000
and engaged ourselves in a two-pronged effort.

1150
01:54:21,000 --> 01:54:25,000
Bob Singleton was a co-chair of it, and Russell H. "Russ" Ellis Jr,

1151
01:54:25,000 --> 01:54:28,000
who's head of campus, core me.

1152
01:54:28,000 --> 01:54:36,000
And we visited ourselves in the fight for fair housing,

1153
01:54:36,000 --> 01:54:39,000
the No on Proposition 14.

1154
01:54:39,000 --> 01:54:43,000
We registered every weekend, we'd mobilize over 100 UCLA students.

1155
01:54:43,000 --> 01:54:45,000
And on Election Day, we had over 900.

1156
01:54:45,000 --> 01:54:48,000
We lost the referendum, eventually one of the courts.

1157
01:54:48,000 --> 01:54:49,000
A major mobilization.

1158
01:54:49,000 --> 01:54:53,000
And we also were in effect a Friends of Stick Group.

1159
01:54:53,000 --> 01:54:56,000
We did all sorts of things to generate support,

1160
01:54:56,000 --> 01:54:59,000
including working with Paul Albert,

1161
01:54:59,000 --> 01:55:01,000
McNichols, and others.

1162
01:55:01,000 --> 01:55:03,000
No matter how much you're Steve, it directly involved with us.

1163
01:55:03,000 --> 01:55:06,000
He's over in the Civil Rights Division of NSA,

1164
01:55:06,000 --> 01:55:07,000
in part of this time.

1165
01:55:07,000 --> 01:55:14,000
But we worked to attempt to persuade Congressmen, Augustus F. "Gus" Hawkins,

1166
01:55:14,000 --> 01:55:16,000
African-American Congressmen of South L.A.,

1167
01:55:16,000 --> 01:55:20,000
Congressman Phil Burton from San Francisco,

1168
01:55:20,000 --> 01:55:23,000
and Congressman William Fitts Ryan of New York, Manhattan,

1169
01:55:23,000 --> 01:55:25,000
and the Reform Democrat, to hold hearings in Mississippi.

1170
01:55:25,000 --> 01:55:27,000
So we had all sorts of letters sent.

1171
01:55:27,000 --> 01:55:29,000
We had people send it from their home addresses,

1172
01:55:29,000 --> 01:55:31,000
and we'd get other people to send them in law and behold.

1173
01:55:31,000 --> 01:55:33,000
They went and did it.

1174
01:55:33,000 --> 01:55:35,000
This all at the time, when we were just trying to...

1175
01:55:35,000 --> 01:55:37,000
The Congressional Committee, some cells,

1176
01:55:37,000 --> 01:55:38,000
weren't going to do it.

1177
01:55:38,000 --> 01:55:41,000
They're under the firm leadership of white segregation

1178
01:55:41,000 --> 01:55:43,000
as southern chairman, in most cases.

1179
01:55:43,000 --> 01:55:45,000
Not every case, but in most cases.

1180
01:55:45,000 --> 01:55:48,000
But these folks went and did it, and that helped a bit.

1181
01:55:48,000 --> 01:55:52,000
We did all sorts of things, and were involved there.

1182
01:55:52,000 --> 01:55:57,000
And then, of course, the connection between the Civil Rights Movement

1183
01:55:57,000 --> 01:55:59,000
and the UC Berkeley Free Speech Movement

1184
01:55:59,000 --> 01:56:00,000
is powerful.

1185
01:56:00,000 --> 01:56:04,000
Jack Weinberg was raising money from Mississippi, and so on.

1186
01:56:04,000 --> 01:56:08,000
We very much joined that effort and became deeply involved

1187
01:56:08,000 --> 01:56:10,000
in those struggles.

1188
01:56:10,000 --> 01:56:15,000
Sometime later, we became involved in a number of us,

1189
01:56:15,000 --> 01:56:17,000
and the campaign of James Jones,

1190
01:56:17,000 --> 01:56:20,000
who was the first African-American male to be elected

1191
01:56:20,000 --> 01:56:23,000
as a Board of Education, to a NAWA campaign,

1192
01:56:23,000 --> 01:56:25,000
which led into the Tom Bradley 1969 mayoral campaign (lost) + 1973 mayoral campaign.

1193
01:56:25,000 --> 01:56:29,000
After the death, and I met my first wife,

1194
01:56:29,000 --> 01:56:31,000
who lost a cancer some years ago,

1195
01:56:31,000 --> 01:56:35,000
in the campaign of the late Senator Robert F. Kennedy.

1196
01:56:35,000 --> 01:56:37,000
We were very involved in that.

1197
01:56:37,000 --> 01:56:43,000
We'd run into John Lewis, and we're deeply involved

1198
01:56:43,000 --> 01:56:45,000
in those efforts.

1199
01:56:45,000 --> 01:56:48,000
And like a lot of people of that generation,

1200
01:56:48,000 --> 01:56:53,000
we had five assassinations in less than five years.

1201
01:56:53,000 --> 01:56:56,000
The combination of Mr. Ebers, Michael Ebers,

1202
01:56:56,000 --> 01:57:03,000
President Kennedy, Malcolm X, Dr. King, Senator Kennedy.

1203
01:57:03,000 --> 01:57:07,000
So, just in there, the unified conspiracy that I'm confident

1204
01:57:07,000 --> 01:57:11,000
there was a conspiracy to kill Dr. King.

1205
01:57:11,000 --> 01:57:15,000
Clearly, to me, James Earl Ray never could have done that.

1206
01:57:15,000 --> 01:57:17,000
Logistically, the things he did with a lot of support,

1207
01:57:17,000 --> 01:57:20,000
logistics, finance, other things.

1208
01:57:20,000 --> 01:57:26,000
And then to wrap up, we were four,

1209
01:57:26,000 --> 01:57:30,000
Councilman Tom Bradley for mayor, I think, before he was.

1210
01:57:30,000 --> 01:57:33,000
He saw the data from the Kennedy campaign and saw,

1211
01:57:33,000 --> 01:57:35,000
we played a big role in this.

1212
01:57:35,000 --> 01:57:38,000
We were able to get a larger turnout of African-American voters

1213
01:57:38,000 --> 01:57:41,000
and Latino voters, partly with help with the (United) Farm Workers.

1214
01:57:41,000 --> 01:57:44,000
And Tom Bradley looked at that and realized that in a city

1215
01:57:44,000 --> 01:57:48,000
